WEBVTT

00:08.418 --> 00:17.352
and life probably looked like most other people that age of like having a good career, it looked good on the outside.

00:18.714 --> 00:24.022
But on the inside, it was all how I can't even describe how empty it felt.

00:24.844 --> 00:32.235
Like there was just this part of me that was missing, that I was filling with something else, and that was alcohol.

00:35.140 --> 00:36.722
I wanted to feel filled.

00:37.378 --> 00:39.321
I wanted to feel the joy that came with life.

00:40.002 --> 00:40.903
That's what I was wanting.

00:40.943 --> 00:44.027
It's really like a true sense of being filled with joy and peace.

00:45.028 --> 00:49.234
On the outside, alcohol looks like it does that, but the reality of it is totally different.

00:51.617 --> 00:56.043
I knew I would never be the dad I wanted to be doing what I was doing.

00:56.584 --> 01:03.794
Like there's no way that the way I was living my life in this lie was gonna produce any good fruit with my children.

01:07.938 --> 01:15.728
My first visit to River Valley Church, my wife and I were invited, and I walked in the doors, and I knew there was something different at the moment I walked in.

01:15.748 --> 01:20.554
I also introduced the Minnesota Adult and Teen Challenge Choir.

01:22.056 --> 01:25.260
I knew that it was a faith-based treatment program.

01:26.141 --> 01:29.165
I remember thinking to myself, I wonder if I'll be there someday.

01:31.207 --> 01:34.872
And I think at the time I knew what the answer was gonna be.

01:35.333 --> 01:36.434
It was just a matter of when.

01:39.970 --> 01:45.937
When you're sitting at that point and you're facing an addiction, you're just scared of what the other side looks like.

01:46.558 --> 01:48.461
And I was really scared of what it looked like.

01:48.641 --> 01:50.343
What was life without that?

01:50.864 --> 01:52.345
What are other people gonna think of me?

01:52.466 --> 01:56.591
Like, if I go to treatment, what's the stigma attached with that?

01:56.651 --> 01:57.852
What are people gonna say?

01:58.513 --> 02:02.458
It is like you make up every reason why not to do it.

02:05.081 --> 02:08.946
A few years it went by, and my wife decided she wanted to go on a

02:09.410 --> 02:10.692
a global team to Ethiopia.

02:11.252 --> 02:15.497
And while she was gone, I would call my rock bottom.

02:17.059 --> 02:23.367
I describe it as the first time I really felt godly sorrow for what I was doing.

02:23.848 --> 02:27.432
My wife was halfway around the world and she was pregnant with our second child.

02:27.913 --> 02:30.496
And here I was a complete disaster.

02:31.857 --> 02:35.602
And I knew that it was now or never.

02:37.986 --> 02:42.430
She came back and I just said, I want to go to a Minnesota adult team challenge.

02:43.071 --> 02:44.212
That is it.

02:45.173 --> 02:46.675
It was a pretty simple conversation.

02:50.939 --> 02:54.262
It was probably two weeks later, they do it like an intake.

02:54.843 --> 03:01.870
And the nurse, she's like, normally, I would be sending you off to a detox facility.

03:01.890 --> 03:05.714
I would not be able to admit you at this time, just because we're concerned about you medically.

03:06.530 --> 03:11.176
But she looked at me and she said, I can see in your eyes that your heart's ready to be here.

03:11.496 --> 03:12.237
And I'm going to let you in.

03:15.140 --> 03:17.083
The first week is what they call the blackout period.

03:17.964 --> 03:20.126
And you're not allowed any communication from the outside.

03:20.827 --> 03:23.310
And I remember the first time I was able to have visitors.

03:23.991 --> 03:31.820
I looked down the hallway, and I see my son running down the hallway with both his hands up in the air, just with the biggest smile on his face.

03:32.721 --> 03:33.522
All of a sudden, my wife

03:33.634 --> 03:42.386
I turned the corner and here she's just radiant coming down the hallway right after it instantly was right there that I'm never going back.

03:44.428 --> 03:46.932
It was like that was the dead stop.

03:47.973 --> 03:51.478
God, whatever you have to do in me, I am ready.

03:51.858 --> 03:54.662
Like you have to have that moment and that was that moment.

03:58.908 --> 04:01.732
So after I left, they always say it's not gonna be the same.

04:02.312 --> 04:03.474
Yeah, and it certainly wasn't.

04:03.970 --> 04:08.737
ended up leaving my job, but also starting my own business as a sign-maker.

04:09.459 --> 04:22.439
I've been blessed with more of like more freedom to do and to serve and spend more time with my family and do the things that God has put me here to do.

04:22.459 --> 04:32.274
I've never heard anybody say I had too much time with my dad and I never want to have them have that void in their life of not having me there.

04:36.226 --> 04:38.709
I was in the short term program for 30 days.

04:39.210 --> 04:44.878
During my wrap up, if you will, or what they call your graduation, the counselor always speaks last.

04:45.959 --> 04:51.967
He looked at me and he said, Lucas, I was praying this morning, and the only thing I have for you is God's got you.

04:53.009 --> 04:55.973
That's all he told me to say to you, I got you.

04:55.993 --> 05:01.400
And that's all I need, is the most simple and default phrase I can fall back on.

05:01.841 --> 05:02.642
I got this.

